{"text": "\uf8f6\n\n\uf8f8= 0.\n\n(87)\n\nThis condition simplifies to\n\n\uf8eb\n\n\uf8ed\u2212\u03b7z2 + Vz \u2212\u03bc\n\nz\u03b1\n\n\u03b1z\n\n\u2212\u03b7z2 \u2212Vz \u2212\u03bc\n\n\uf8f6\n\n\uf8f8\n\n\uf8eb\n\n\uf8edu\u2191\n\nu\u2193\n\n\uf8f6\n\n\uf8f8= 0.\n\n(88)\n\nThe value of z can be determined by setting the determinant of the above matrix to zero.\n\nThis leads to the equation for z\n\n(\u03b7z2 \u2212\u03bc)2 \u2212V 2\n\nz \u2212z2\u03b12 = 0.\n\n(89)\n\nNote that the solutions of the above equation come in pairs \u00b1z.\n\nHowever, the Bessel\n\nfunctions J0(zr) and J1(zr) are odd and even functions of z respectively. Therefore, there\n\nare two linearly independent solutions that one can obtain for r < R.\n\nThe r > R region includes non-zero amplitude of superconductivity.\n\nThis region is\n\ncomplicated to solve analytically except by a power-series solution in 1/r. However, our\n\nfocus of whether there is a normalizable solution in this region depends on the conditions\n\nfor which there are exponentially decaying solutions as r \u2192\u221e. Inspired by the asymptotic\n\nform of Bessel functions Jn(zr) \u221de\u2212zr/r1/2, we consider an ansatz\n\n\u03a80(r) = e\u2212zr\n\nr1/2\n\n\uf8eb\n\n\uf8ed\u03c1\u2191\n\n\u03c1\u2193\n\n\uf8f6\n\n\uf8f8.\n\n(90)\n\nSubstituting this ansatz into the BdG equation we get\n\n\uf8eb\n\n\uf8ed\u03b7(\u2212\u22022\n\nr \u2212\n\n1\n\n4r2 + 2z\u2202r \u2212z2) + Vz \u2212\u03bc\n\n\u03bb\u2206+ \u03b1(\u2202r + 1\n\n2r \u2212z)\n\n\u2212\u03bb\u2206\u2212\u03b1(\u2202r \u22121\n\n2r \u2212z)\n\n\u03b7(\u2212\u22022\n\nr +\n\n3\n\n4r2 + 2z\u2202r \u2212z2) \u2212Vz \u2212\u03bc\n\n\uf8f6\n\n\uf8f8\n\n\uf8eb\n\n\uf8ed\u03c1\u2191\n\n\u03c1\u2193\n\n\uf8f6\n\n\uf8f8= 0.\n\n(91)\n\nWe notice that the r dependence disappears in the limit r \u2192\u221eso that\n\n\uf8eb\n\n\uf8ed\u2212\u03b7z2 + Vz \u2212\u03bc\n\n\u03bb\u2206\u2212z\u03b1\n\n\u2212\u03bb\u2206+ z\u03b1\n\n\u2212\u03b7z2 \u2212Vz \u2212\u03bc\n\n\uf8f6\n\n\uf8f8\n\n\uf8eb\n\n\uf8ed\u03c1\u2191\n\n\u03c1\u2193\n\n\uf8f6\n\n\uf8f8= 0.\n\n(92)\n\n35\n\nSimilar to the case for r < R, this equation has a non-trivial solution if z satisfies the secular\n\nequation:\n\nDet\n\n\uf8eb\n\n\uf8ed\u2212\u03b7z2 + Vz \u2212\u03bc\n\n\u03bb\u2206\u2212z\u03b1\n\n\u2212\u03bb\u2206+ z\u03b1\n\n\u2212\u03b7z2 \u2212Vz \u2212\u03bc\n\n\uf8f6\n\n\uf8f8\n\n= (\u2212\u03b7z2 \u2212\u03bc)2 \u2212V 2\n\nz + (z\u03b1\u03bb \u2212\u2206)2 = 0.\n\n(93)\n\nWe see from the form of the equation that the solutions of z for the two values of \u03bb are\n\nrelated by the sign of \u03bb.\n\nWe can determine zero-energy Majorana solutions to the BdG equation associated with\n\nthe vortex by matching boundary conditions for the spinor \u03a80(r) between solutions for r < R\n\nand r > R at r = R.", "embedding": [0.01808092, 0.018876962, 0.038292464, 0.017950045, -0.034943864, -0.055633787, -0.010739305, 0.00037322877, -0.04203766, 0.069349974, 0.016897881, 0.027102247, 0.0075789653, -0.01921988, -0.028130619, 0.029820122, -0.022113679, -0.03847678, -0.06849546, 0.01326791, 0.008783393, 0.0022777694, -0.06842166, -0.016932119, -0.026355753, 0.040046543, -0.011600191, 0.024298472, 0.045233134, 0.031017434, 0.027219364, -0.024588564, -0.012668305, -0.036925916, 0.014233953, 0.0185126, -0.011459904, -0.005056779, 0.051825564, -0.015740134, 0.02892151, 0.0037575348, -0.022590257, -0.021696663, -0.02275612, -0.00885292, -0.026051523, -0.0047788145, -0.03546989, -0.067972414, 0.00076901505, 0.038816836, 0.049011074, -0.028856643, -0.0069661816, -0.006582956, 0.018266387, -0.0041169776, -0.05684817, -0.019912338, 0.00056449766, -0.009515243, 0.032350942, -0.01861955, 0.02181391, 0.048053827, -0.0062494893, 0.061586898, -0.014017366, -0.033747166, -0.011811981, 0.011472016, 0.008953577, -0.0047584586, -0.032910697, 0.028007751, -0.00042079805, -0.062548794, -0.030753674, -0.027724592, -0.030749775, -0.009416181, -0.027558262, 0.013912358, -0.0018